\name{tipToEdgeCovariate}
\alias{tipToEdgeCovariate}
\title{Convert Tip Measurements to Branch-Level Predictors}
\description{
When you want to test whether a biological trait (like body size or
generation time) predicts the rate of character evolution, you need
covariate values for each \emph{branch} of the tree, not each tip.
This helper function converts your tip-level measurements into branch-level
values.

For each branch (edge) in the tree, the function finds all tips that
descend from that branch and aggregates their trait values using the
specified method. For example, the "mean" method assigns each branch the
average body size of all species in the clade below that branch.

\strong{Which method should I use?}
\itemize{
  \item \code{"mean"} (default): Average of descendant tip values. Best
    general-purpose choice. If the trait evolves gradually, the mean of
    descendants is a reasonable proxy for the ancestral condition along
    that branch.
  \item \code{"median"}: Median of descendant tip values. More robust to
    outliers than the mean. Use when you have extreme values in your data.
  \item \code{"max"} / \code{"min"}: Maximum or minimum of descendants.
    Useful if you hypothesize that the extreme value in a clade drives
    rate variation (e.g., "the largest-bodied species in a clade predicts
    rate of habitat evolution").
  \item \code{"contrast"}: Absolute difference between the mean values of
    the two child clades. This captures within-branch divergence rather
    than the clade mean. Useful for testing whether branches spanning
    large ecological transitions have different rates.
}
}
\usage{
tipToEdgeCovariate(tree, tip_values, method = "mean")
}
\arguments{
\item{tree}{A phylogenetic tree (class \code{"phylo"} from ape).}

\item{tip_values}{A named numeric vector of trait values, one per tip. The
names must match the tip labels of the tree exactly. For example:
\code{setNames(c(2.1, 3.5, 1.8, ...), c("sp1", "sp2", "sp3", ...))}.}

\item{method}{How to aggregate tip values for each branch. One of
\code{"mean"} (default), \code{"median"}, \code{"max"}, \code{"min"}, or
\code{"contrast"}. See Description for guidance on choosing.}
}
\value{
A numeric vector with one value per branch (edge), in the same order as
\code{tree$edge}. This can be used directly to build the covariate matrix
for \code{\link{fitRateScape}}.
}
